## Example 2 — Photography Enlargement

A photograph measures 4 inches by 6 inches. It is enlarged so that the shorter side becomes 10 inches. Find the length of the longer side and the ratio of the new area to the original area.

### Step 1: Find the Scale Factor

$$k = \frac{10}{4} = \frac{5}{2} = 2.5$$

### Step 2: Find the New Longer Side

$$\text{New longer side} = 6 \times 2.5 = 15 \text{ inches}$$

### Step 3: Find the Area Ratio

$$\text{Original area} = 4 \times 6 = 24 \text{ in}^2$$

$$\text{New area} = 10 \times 15 = 150 \text{ in}^2$$

$$\frac{\text{New area}}{\text{Original area}} = \frac{150}{24} = \frac{25}{4} = (2.5)^2 = k^2 \checkmark$$

### Step 4: Verify Proportionality

$$\frac{10}{4} = \frac{15}{6} = \frac{5}{2} \checkmark$$

The enlarged photo has the same proportions as the original.

✅ Answer: The longer side is **15 inches**. The new area is $\frac{25}{4}$ (or 6.25 times) the original area.

